  0.62, 6, 42,
  ARRAY['March 2012: SWIFT disconnection triggers rial collapse and 40%+ inflation, demonstrating unprecedented financial leverage','November 2013: Interim Geneva agreement (Joint Plan of Action) provides partial sanctions relief in exchange for uranium enrichment freeze, proving Iran willing to negotiate under pressure','July 2015: JCPOA signed — Iran agrees to cap enrichment at 3.67%, reduce centrifuges by two-thirds, and accept IAEA cameras in exchange for sanctions removal'],
  'JCPOA signed July 14, 2015, with sanctions lifted on Implementation Day (January 16, 2016) after IAEA verified Iranian compliance. Iran rapidly restored oil exports to over 2 million b/d. US withdrew from JCPOA in May 2018, reimposing maximum-pressure sanctions.',
  ARRAY['SWIFT exclusion is the most powerful single financial weapon available to Western sanctioners, capable of causing near-immediate currency collapse in an oil-dependent economy','Secondary sanctions (threatening third-country banks) are essential for effectiveness — without them, China and India continued purchasing Iranian oil at discount, partially cushioning the blow','Sanctions succeeded in bringing Iran to the table but not in eliminating its nuclear capabilities; they produced a negotiated compromise rather than capitulation, underscoring the gap between pressure and compliance'],
  ARRAY['nuclear','SWIFT','oil','JCPOA','secondary-sanctions','Middle East'],
