  '{"scenarios": [{"label": "partial_compliance", "probability": 0.08}, {"label": "escalation", "probability": 0.50}, {"label": "status_quo", "probability": 0.34}, {"label": "negotiated_freeze", "probability": 0.08}], "gdp_impact_pct": -3.7, "export_revenue_decline_pct": 12}',
  0.18, 8, NULL,
  ARRAY['December 2014: Ruble collapses 58% against the dollar, forcing Russian central bank to raise rates to 17% — the most severe immediate financial shock','February 2015: Minsk II agreement signed but never implemented; sanctions maintained despite nominal compliance process','2016–2019: Russian economy stabilizes and grows modestly as oil prices recover, demonstrating sanctions limited long-term coercive leverage when not paired with oil embargo'],
  'Sanctions remain in place as of 2026. Russia never reversed Crimea annexation. The regime was later superseded by far broader 2022 post-Ukraine invasion sanctions.',
  ARRAY['Sectoral sanctions without full energy embargo provide insufficient coercive leverage against a major oil exporter — Russia''s hydrocarbon revenues continued funding the state even as finance and technology sectors were squeezed','The 2014 sanctions were significantly diluted by European reluctance to cut energy imports, demonstrating that coalition cohesion is the critical variable in multilateral sanctions effectiveness','Ruble depreciation and capital flight imposed real economic costs but did not alter Russian foreign policy; economic pain and policy capitulation are not reliably linked in authoritarian petrostate contexts'],
  ARRAY['Russia','Crimea','Ukraine','energy','financial','sectoral'],
  ARRAY['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_sanctions_during_the_Russo-Ukrainian_war','EU Council Regulation 269/2014','Peterson Institute for International Economics 2015'],
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_sanctions_during_the_Russo-Ukrainian_war',
  'Western allies imposed sectoral sanctions on Russian finance, energy, and defense sectors following the annexation of Crimea in March 2014. The ruble collapsed 46% and capital outflows reached $151 billion in 2014, but Russia adapted rapidly through import substitution and closer ties with China. Territorial objectives were not reversed. Canonical case of high-intensity multilateral sanctions failing to achieve primary political goals against a major economy with diversified external relationships.'
),

