  '{"scenarios": [{"label": "partial_compliance", "probability": 0.08}, {"label": "escalation", "probability": 0.45}, {"label": "status_quo", "probability": 0.35}, {"label": "negotiated_ceasefire", "probability": 0.12}], "gdp_impact_pct": -2.1, "oil_revenue_loss_bn_usd": 20}',
  0.15, 3, NULL,
  ARRAY['February–March 2022: Freezing of $300 billion in Russian central bank reserves represents the largest-ever sovereign asset seizure; ruble initially plunges 40% before recovering on capital controls','December 2022: G7 oil price cap implementation forces Russia to rapidly expand shadow fleet and redirect exports to Asia, costing an estimated $15-20 billion in annual revenue','2023–2025: Russia''s economy proves more resilient than forecast (growing 3.6% in 2023) due to war-driven fiscal stimulus, import substitution, and record revenues from Asian oil sales'],
  'Ongoing as of March 2026. Russia continues fighting in Ukraine. Oil revenues recovering via shadow fleet and Asian buyers. Frozen reserves remain subject to G7 debate over seizure for Ukraine reconstruction.',
  ARRAY['Freezing sovereign reserves is a powerful escalation tool but not an immediate coercive lever — Russia adapted through capital controls and redirected trade before reserves mattered operationally','The shadow fleet ecosystem (pioneered by Iran, replicated by Russia and Venezuela) represents a structural failure in the oil price cap mechanism; enforcing the cap requires sanctioning Indian and Chinese refiners, a step Western governments have been unwilling to take','War-economy dynamics can substantially offset sanctions costs — Russian military spending (40% of 2024 federal budget) provided Keynesian stimulus that partially substituted for lost private economic activity'],
  ARRAY['Russia','Ukraine','SWIFT','oil-price-cap','shadow-fleet','frozen-reserves','comprehensive'],
  ARRAY['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_sanctions_during_the_Russo-Ukrainian_war','OFAC Russia sanctions 2022','EU sanctions packages 2022-2024'],
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_sanctions_during_the_Russo-Ukrainian_war',
  'The broadest sanctions package in modern history, imposed following Russia''s full-scale invasion of Ukraine on February 24, 2022. Over $300 billion in central bank reserves frozen, SWIFT access removed for major banks, and an oil price cap implemented. Despite initial shock, Russia''s economy proved resilient through war-economy stimulus, shadow fleet oil exports, and Asian market redirection. GDP fell only 2.1% versus predictions of 10-15%. Ongoing as of 2026 with no resolution in sight.'
),

