  0.04, 18, NULL,
  ARRAY['2017: UN Resolutions 2371 and 2375 ban coal, iron, and seafood exports worth ~$3 billion/year — the tightest sanctions in DPRK history, backed by Chinese support after the sixth nuclear test','2019: Trump-Kim Singapore and Hanoi summits collapse without agreement; North Korea resumes missile testing and ramps up cyber operations to compensate for sanctions-driven revenue loss','2022: Russia and China veto further UN Security Council sanctions after Russia invades Ukraine; North Korea provides artillery shells to Russia, effectively breaking out of isolation'],
  'Ongoing. North Korea has conducted over 100 ballistic missile tests since 2022 and continues nuclear program development. Denuclearization objective has not been achieved. DPRK-Russia arms cooperation has materially weakened the sanctions coalition.',
  ARRAY['Sanctions that rely on Chinese enforcement against a Chinese-border state face an irreducible compliance problem: China''s strategic interest in preventing North Korean collapse reliably overrides its commitment to sanctions pressure','Cybercrime as a sanctions evasion tool is a qualitative innovation — unlike physical smuggling, it scales without geographic constraint and is extremely difficult to interdict, generating billions in hard currency annually','Prolonged maximum-pressure campaigns against nuclear-armed states can entrench rather than reverse proliferation by removing the regime''s incentive to bargain away its only existential deterrent'],
  ARRAY['nuclear','DPRK','Korea','cyber','arms-embargo','ship-to-ship','China-dependence'],
  ARRAY['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_sanctions_against_North_Korea','UN Panel of Experts Reports 2006-2023','US Treasury OFAC DPRK designations'],
