-- 5. Cuba Embargo 1962
(
  'CUB1962_EMBARGO',
  'US Embargo Against Cuba',
  '1962-02-07', NULL,
  ARRAY['US'],
  'Cuba', 0.07, 'comprehensive',
  ARRAY['Initially: weaken the Castro regime to force its collapse or policy reversal. Post-Cold War: promote democracy and human rights in Cuba'],
  false, false, 'critical',
  ARRAY['Total ban on US exports to Cuba (except food and medicine after 2000)','Total ban on US imports from Cuba','Prohibition on US citizens traveling to Cuba and spending money there','Freeze on Cuban government assets in the US','Prohibition on foreign subsidiaries of US firms trading with Cuba (Helms-Burton Act, 1996)','Third-country shipping restrictions (ships calling in Cuban ports barred from US ports for 6 months)'],
  'Cuba''s nationalization of US-owned properties and its geopolitical alignment with the Soviet Union during the Cold War; formally established February 1962 by President Kennedy',
  ARRAY['Soviet Union provided subsidies averaging $4.3 billion/year (1986-1990), representing 21% of Cuban GNP — purchasing Cuban sugar at 6x world market price and selling oil below market price','Cuba re-exported below-market Soviet oil on world markets, generating hard currency equal to 40% of total revenues','European, Canadian, and Latin American trade and tourism provided substitute income streams outside US jurisdiction','Post-1990: Venezuela under Chávez supplied 100,000 barrels/day at preferential rates in exchange for Cuban doctors, partially replacing Soviet subsidies'],
  '{"gdp_change_pct": -33, "oil_export_change_pct": null, "inflation_pct": null, "currency_devaluation_pct": null, "alternative_partners": ["Soviet Union","Venezuela","China","Canada","European Union","Russia"]}',
  'evasion', 'no',
  '{"scenarios": [{"label": "compliance", "probability": 0.02}, {"label": "status_quo", "probability": 0.75}, {"label": "evasion_adaptation", "probability": 0.23}], "gdp_impact_pct": -5.0}',
  '{"scenarios": [{"label": "compliance", "probability": 0.02}, {"label": "status_quo", "probability": 0.70}, {"label": "evasion_adaptation", "probability": 0.28}], "gdp_impact_pct": -8.0}',
  0.03, 24, NULL,
  ARRAY['1991: Soviet collapse eliminates $4.3 billion/year in subsidies; Cuba''s GDP falls 33% by 1993 in the Special Period — the sanctions'' moment of maximum effectiveness as alternative patron disappeared','1996: Helms-Burton Act codifies embargo into law and extraterritorializes it; tightens but also entrenches the policy, removing presidential flexibility','2014-2016: Obama-era détente partially lifts travel and remittance restrictions; diplomatic relations restored — then reversed by Trump administration in 2017'],
  'Ongoing as of March 2026. The longest-running bilateral trade embargo in modern history. Cuba''s Communist government remains in power 64 years after the embargo was imposed. The UN General Assembly has voted to condemn the embargo annually since 1992, typically by margins of 185-2.',
  ARRAY['Unilateral sanctions against a small state are systematically circumvented when a major power has strategic interest in sponsoring the target — the effectiveness of sanctions is fundamentally a function of the target''s access to alternative patrons','The embargo''s endurance as a political institution despite its acknowledged policy failure illustrates how domestic interest groups can lock in ineffective sanctions regardless of strategic merit','Extraterritorial sanctions (Helms-Burton Title III) antagonize allied governments without meaningfully increasing target compliance, damaging coalition relationships needed for other foreign policy goals'],
  ARRAY['Cuba','Cold War','comprehensive','unilateral','Helms-Burton','longest-running'],
  ARRAY['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_embargo_against_Cuba','US OFAC Cuba sanctions','Helms-Burton Act 1996'],
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_embargo_against_Cuba',
  'The longest-running comprehensive trade embargo in modern history — imposed by the US on Cuba in February 1962 and still in effect as of 2026. Despite causing Cuba''s GDP to fall 33% during the Special Period (1990-1993) when Soviet subsidies collapsed, the regime survived by finding successive alternative patrons (Soviet Union, Venezuela, China). The canonical failure case for unilateral sanctions against a small state with access to major-power sponsorship.'
),

