  'Libya/Gaddafi sanctions represent one of the clearest success cases in the dataset. US unilateral sanctions (1986-1992) failed for 6 years; the addition of UN multilateral pressure in 1992 produced results within 7 years. Gaddafi handed over Lockerbie suspects in 1999, accepted responsibility and paid $2.7 billion compensation in 2003, and voluntarily abandoned WMD programs. Key lessons: multilateral > unilateral, face-saving off-ramps matter, and specific verifiable demands outperform regime-change goals.'
),

