  'Yugoslavia/Serbia comprehensive sanctions (1992-1995) produced devastating economic damage (GDP -60%, inflation of 116 quadrillion percent) but partial compliance only — war ended through NATO airstrikes and Croatian military offensives as much as economic pressure. State-protected smuggling networks (run by Milosevic allies and organized crime) provided partial evasion. The Dayton Agreement''s specific, verifiable behavioral benchmarks tied to sanctions relief provided a clear exit ramp — a model for successful coercive diplomacy.'
