  0.55, 12, 168,
  ARRAY['1974: Portuguese Carnation Revolution ends colonial rule in Mozambique; Mozambique under Frelimo closes its border with Rhodesia (1976), eliminating a critical sanctions-busting corridor and access to Indian Ocean ports','1976: US repeals Byrd Amendment, closing the chrome import loophole and finally bringing the US into full compliance with mandatory UN sanctions','1979: Lancaster House Agreement negotiated in London — Smith government accepts majority-rule elections; sanctions lifted; Zimbabwe independence declared April 1980'],
  'Rhodesian government accepted Lancaster House Agreement in December 1979 after 14 years of resistance. Free elections held February 1980; Robert Mugabe''s ZANU won. Sanctions lifted. The case is debated: economic pressure was significant but the decisive factors may have been South Africa withdrawing support and intensifying guerrilla warfare by ZANU/ZAPU forces.',
  ARRAY['Contiguous neighbor defection is the single largest predictor of sanctions failure — South Africa''s explicit refusal to participate sustained Rhodesia for 14 years despite otherwise broad multilateral support','The Byrd Amendment case demonstrates that domestic commercial interests within sanctioning countries will consistently seek exemptions, eroding the economic impact even of mandatory UN sanctions','The eventual success of Rhodesia sanctions was heavily dependent on external geopolitical shifts (Portuguese decolonization, South African policy change) rather than pure economic coercion dynamics'],
