  'Italy''s invasion of Abyssinia (Ethiopia) on October 3, 1935 — the first major test of the League''s collective security system',
  ARRAY['United States (not a League member) was the world''s largest oil producer and its neutrality legislation prevented Roosevelt from imposing an oil embargo; American oil companies increased exports to Italy fivefold during the crisis','Germany (expelled from League 1933) continued trading with Italy outside the sanctions framework; the Rome-Berlin Axis announced October 1936 reflected this alignment','The Hoare-Laval Pact (December 1935) — secret Anglo-French agreement offering Italy most of Abyssinia in exchange for ending the war — revealed that Britain and France were unwilling to enforce sanctions militarily','Oil was deliberately excluded from League sanctions despite being Italy''s most critical import — coal and iron were also excluded; the sanctions omitted Italy''s most vulnerable supply chains'],
  '{"gdp_change_pct": null, "oil_export_change_pct": null, "inflation_pct": null, "currency_devaluation_pct": null, "alternative_partners": ["United States","Germany","Austria","Hungary"]}',
  'backfire', 'no',
  '{"scenarios": [{"label": "compliance", "probability": 0.10}, {"label": "status_quo", "probability": 0.50}, {"label": "backfire", "probability": 0.40}], "gdp_impact_pct": -1}',
  '{"scenarios": [{"label": "compliance", "probability": 0.05}, {"label": "status_quo", "probability": 0.30}, {"label": "backfire", "probability": 0.65}], "gdp_impact_pct": 0}',
  0.03, 3, 8,
  ARRAY['December 1935: Hoare-Laval Pact revealed — France and Britain secretly planned to partition Abyssinia giving Italy the best agricultural regions; massive public outrage forces both Foreign Ministers to resign but fatally exposes allied bad faith','May 1936: Italy completes conquest of Abyssinia; Emperor Haile Selassie addresses League Assembly — sanctions are suspended July 1936 as Italy annexes Ethiopia and League accepts fait accompli','October 1936: Rome-Berlin Axis announced; Mussolini draws strategic conclusion from the episode that Western democracies will not enforce international law — reinforcing the path toward WWII'],
  'Sanctions suspended July 4, 1936 after Italy formally annexed Ethiopia. The episode destroyed the League of Nations'' credibility as a collective security institution. The failure to include oil in sanctions — the one commodity that could have halted Italian military operations — is regarded as the decisive political failure.',
  ARRAY['Sanctions that deliberately exclude the target''s most critical import (oil) in a war scenario are not just ineffective but may be counterproductive — they signal resolve without imposing meaningful costs, credibly demonstrating Western irresolution to both the target and other would-be aggressors','The Hoare-Laval affair demonstrates that coalition unity in sanctions requires genuine alignment of political will — if leading members privately prefer appeasement, the sanctions regime becomes a performative exercise rather than a coercive instrument','Non-participation by major non-member states (US, Germany) in the 1930s is the structural predecessor of China and Russia''s non-participation in modern sanctions regimes — collective security requires near-universal participation to be effective against a major oil-importing power'],
  ARRAY['League-of-Nations','Italy','Abyssinia','Ethiopia','collective-security','historical','failure','1930s'],
  ARRAY['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abyssinia_Crisis','League of Nations Official Journal 1935-1936','Hoare-Laval Pact documents'],
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abyssinia_Crisis',
  'The League of Nations sanctions against Italy (1935-1936) are the foundational failure case in sanctions history. Despite 50-state participation, sanctions deliberately excluded oil — Italy''s most critical military import — because of Anglo-French political timidity. The Hoare-Laval Pact revealed secret appeasement plans, exposing coalition bad faith. The failure destroyed the League''s credibility and emboldened Hitler and Mussolini toward WWII. Direct structural parallel to modern cases where key commodities (Russian energy, Iranian oil) are excluded from sanctions packages due to coalition economic interests.'
),

