  ARRAY['Total oil embargo against a heavily oil-dependent military power with no alternative suppliers and expansionist military capacity can provoke military conflict rather than political compliance — the Japan case is the definitive historical example of sanctions as a casus belli','Implementation details matter critically: US officials intended a partial restriction that was implemented as a total cut-off by subordinate officials; the gap between policy intent and implementation had world-historical consequences','When the sanctioned state calculates that military force can seize the sanctioned resource (oil fields) at lower cost than sustained sanctions compliance, military action becomes rational — a calculation that only applies when the target has strong military capacity and geographic proximity to the resource'],
