  'The US oil embargo against Japan (1941) is the definitive backfire case — the only historical instance of sanctions directly provoking a military attack on the sanctioning state. Japan received 94% of its oil from the US and Dutch East Indies; with no alternative suppliers and expansionist military capacity, it calculated that seizing oil fields by force was less costly than compliance. Pearl Harbor followed 4 months after the embargo. Key lesson: total embargoes against military powers with no evasion route and access to target resources by force are existentially escalatory.'
